aa(lp98
VAnd here's an example of what I mean.
p99
aVThis upward ascension
p100
aVcan happen even in the face of extreme physical challenges.
p101
aVAbout three years ago, I read an article in the New York Times.
p102
aVIt was about a man named Neil Selinger \u2014
p103
aV57 years old, a retired lawyer,
p104
aVwho had joined the writers' group at Sarah Lawrence,
p105
aVwhere he found his writer's voice.
p106
aVTwo years later,
p107
aVhe was diagnosed with ALS, commonly known as Lou Gehrig's disease.
p108
aVIt's a terrible disease. It's fatal.
p109
aVIt wastes the body, but the mind remains intact.
p110
aVIn this article, Mr. Selinger wrote the following
p111
aVto describe what was happening to him.
p112
aVAnd I quote:
p113
aV"As my muscles weakened,
p114
aVmy writing became stronger.
p115
aVAs I slowly lost my speech,
p116
aVI gained my voice.
p117
aVAs I diminished, I grew.
p118
aVAs I lost so much,
p119
aVI finally started to find myself."
p120
aVNeil Selinger, to me,
p121
aVis the embodiment of mounting the staircase
p122
aVin his third act.
p123
aa(lp124
VNow we're all born with spirit, all of us,
p125
aVbut sometimes it gets tamped down beneath the challenges of life,
p126
aVviolence, abuse, neglect.
p127
aVPerhaps our parents suffered from depression.
p128
aVPerhaps they weren't able to love us beyond how we performed in the world.
p129
aVPerhaps we still suffer from a psychic pain, a wound.
p130
aVPerhaps we feel that many of our relationships
p131
aVhave not had closure.
p132
aVAnd so we can feel unfinished.
p133
aVPerhaps the task of the third act
p134
