aa(lp167
VNow while I was writing about this,
p168
aVI came upon a book called "Man's Search for Meaning"
p169
aVby Viktor Frankl.
p170
aVViktor Frankl was a German psychiatrist
p171
aVwho'd spent five years in a Nazi concentration camp.
p172
aVAnd he wrote that, while he was in the camp,
p173
aVhe could tell, should they ever be released,
p174
aVwhich of the people would be OK, and which would not.
p175
aVAnd he wrote this:
p176
aV"Everything you have in life can be taken from you
p177
aVexcept one thing:
p178
aVyour freedom to choose how you will respond to the situation.
p179
aVThis is what determines the quality of the life we've lived \u2014
p180
aVnot whether we've been rich or poor,
p181
aVfamous or unknown,
p182
aVhealthy or suffering.
p183
aVWhat determines our quality of life is how we relate to these realities,
p184
aVwhat kind of meaning we assign them,
p185
aVwhat kind of attitude we cling to about them,
p186
aVwhat state of mind we allow them to trigger."
